  "notes": [
    {
      "id": "note_4",
      "text": "WORKFLOW: exploratory data analysis (the first look). Before any test, get to know the data. Step 1 — Describe Data reports n, centre (mean/median), spread (sd, IQR) and shape (skewness, (excess) kurtosis) for every variable; a median far from the mean, or a large skew, flags an asymmetric distribution. Step 2 — the faceted histograms show each distribution directly (one small-multiple per variable): look for skew, bimodality, gaps and outliers. Step 3 — a normality test screens each variable (Shapiro-Wilk by default); a small p-value means non-normal, which steers you toward rank / non-parametric methods later. Step 4 — the correlation heatmap and pairs plot map the pairwise relationships (scatter + linear fit above the diagonal, distributions on it) so you can see which variables move together BEFORE modelling. Read it as reconnaissance, not inference: this pass tells you which tests are appropriate and where the data-quality problems are. Tukey, Exploratory Data Analysis (1977).",
      "x": 40,
      "y": 24,
      "width": 360,
      "height": 190
    }
  ],
